{[showcards S:C6]

You are East. The bidding has been as shown.

You lead the \S7; \S3, \S2 and won by North with \SQ.

North then plays the \C6 from his hand. Which \C should you play?

Play the \CJ.

You should not allow yourself to be misled by North winning the first trick with the \SQ. West does not hold either the \SA or the \SJ or he would have played it. North is just trying to be deceptive.

That means you need the next \S play to come from West, so you play your \CJ and let West win his \CA. You can be sure West has the \CA because North would have played the suit differently if he held the Ace.

West will win the \CA and return his \S through North's \S A Q. This allows you to set up your \S suit while you still have the \CK for an entry.}
[Play "W"]S7

